Now I need to understand the issue. Looking at the `testIssue639` test, it seems to be testing a specific rotation created from two pairs of vectors. The issue seems to be related to the calculation in the `Rotation` constructor that takes 4 vectors (two pairs). Let me look more closely at the constructor that is used in the test:

The test calls:
```java
Rotation rot = new Rotation(u1, u2, Vector3D.PLUS_I, Vector3D.PLUS_K);
```

This corresponds to the constructor:
```java
public Rotation(Vector3D u1, Vector3D u2, Vector3D v1, Vector3D v2)
```

I can see that in the constructor, there are some potential issues with the computation of the scalar part (q0) when dealing with special cases. Let me look at this part more closely in the constructor:

I noticed there are some issues in the constructor where `k` is calculated twice. Let me look more carefully at the specific lines:

Looking at the constructor again, I see this part:
```java
// compute the scalar part
 k = new Vector3D(uRef.getY() * q3 - uRef.getZ() * q2,
                  uRef.getZ() * q1 - uRef.getX() * q3,
                  uRef.getX() * q2 - uRef.getY() * q1);
q0 = vRef.dotProduct(k) / (2 * k.getNormSq());
```

The issue appears to be in the comment that says `// compute the scalar part` but the variable `k` was already used earlier in the code. Looking at the constructor more carefully, I see there are some potential issues with the calculation of `q0`.

Let me look at the code around where there are potential issues. I notice in the constructor there are lines like:

```java
if (c == 0) {
  // the (q1, q2, q3) vector is close to the (u1, u2) plane
  // we try other vectors
  Vector3D v3 = Vector3D.crossProduct(v1, v2);
  Vector3D v3Su3 = v3.subtract(u3);
  k = v1Su1.crossProduct(v3Su3);
  Vector3D u2Prime = u1.crossProduct(u3);
  c = k.dotProduct(u2Prime);

  if (c == 0) {
    // the (q1, q2, q3) vector is also close to the (u1, u3) plane,
    // it is almost aligned with u1: we try (u2, u3) and (v2, v3)
    k = v2Su2.crossProduct(v3Su3);;  // <-- Note the double semicolon
    c = k.dotProduct(u2.crossProduct(u3));;  // <-- Note the double semicolon

    if (c == 0) {
      // the (q1, q2, q3) vector is aligned with everything
      // this is really the identity rotation
      q0 = 1.0;
      q1 = 0.0;
      q2 = 0.0;
      q3 = 0.0;
      return;
    }

    // we will have to use u2 and v2 to compute the scalar part
    uRef = u2;
    vRef = v2;

  }

}
```

